                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase;">E-commerce</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">Temu prices in South Africa now show you your taxes</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">

<a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
<img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2025/02/Temu-1.jpg" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
<figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image source: MSN</figcaption>
</figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Chinese e-commerce platform, Temu, <a href="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/internet/638569-temu-makes-big-vat-and-import-duty-change-in-south-africa.html" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">now includes value-added tax (VAT) and import duty charges</a> directly at checkout for South African users. Previously, shoppers would place an order, feel good about the price, and only later&mdash;between dispatch and delivery&mdash;get a prompt to pay customs charges. The final cost often arrived in parts. Now, it appears upfront.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>This is Temu adjusting to pressure:</strong> South Africa is tightening how imports are taxed, especially low-value goods that once slipped through with lighter duties. For years, parcels under R500 ($29.59) attracted a flat 20% duty and no VAT, creating a loophole that international sellers leveraged. That window is now closing: the South African Revenue Service (SARS), the country&rsquo;s tax authority, moves to tighten import rules.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Temu is taking control of the process: </strong>It is centralising tax calculation in the same way Amazon has done for years, simplifying filing for users, and ensuring Temu stays on the right side of a changing system.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Why this matters: </strong>Temu&rsquo;s edge has always been low prices sourced from Chinese sellers, but hidden or ambiguous costs, often <a href="https://businesstech.co.za/news/enterprise/782878/temu-and-shein-clampdown-in-south-africa/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">linked back to Temu&rsquo;s alleged underhanded tactics</a>, have been a sore spot for customers. South African regulators are pushing for transparent prices, and Temu has to key into this new mandate or risk a regulatory witch-hunt.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">If global e-commerce platforms in markets like South Africa are going to keep growing under tighter rules, they can&rsquo;t run on hidden charges; they have to be upfront.</p>
